# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: david-starr-jordan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:david-starr-jordan/adam-herbert] Born in Muskogee, Oklahoma, he and his sister Tamashia Buckner were raised by their mother, Addie Hibler Herbert, who was a divorcee.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adam-herbert] Herbert attended Manual Training High School.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adam-herbert] Herbert's mother was a teacher and librarian and a strong influence on him.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adam-herbert] Herbert earned a Bachelor of Arts in political science (1966) and a Master of Public Administration (1968) from the University of Southern California.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adam-herbert] He earned his Ph.D. in urban affairs and public administration from the University of Pittsburgh in 1971.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adam-herbert] Herbert's academic career started at University of Southern California as a faculty member in the School of Public Administration and the Center for Urban Affairs.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adam-herbert] In 1972 he became the chair of urban affairs program and associate professor of urban affairs at the Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University (Virginia Tech).
[src:david-starr-jordan/adam-herbert] On June 6, 2003, Herbert was selected to be IU's 17th president, his term began on August 1, 2003.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adam-herbert] Upon assuming leadership of Indiana University, one of Herbert's biggest initiatives focused on "mission differentiation" for IU's eight campuses, which included making the flagship Bloomington campus more selective.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adam-herbert] Under the proposal Indiana University Bloomington would have educated the professionals, executives and researchers while the regional campuses would be tasked with educating the labor force.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adam-herbert] A signature accomplishment of Herbert's time at IU was the creation of what was then called the "Hoosier Presidential Scholars," in 2005.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adam-herbert] Herbert served on the transition team of Mayor-elect of Jacksonville Alvin Brown.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] He also founded the science of anthropometry and developed the body mass index (BMI) scale, originally called the Quetelet Index.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] His work on measuring human characteristic to determine the ideal *l'homme moyen* ("the average man"), played a key role in the origins of eugenics.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Adolphe was born in Ghent (which, at the time was a part of the new French Republic).
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] He was the son of François-Augustin-Jacques-Henri Quetelet, a Frenchman and Anne Françoise Vandervelde, a Flemish woman.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] His father was born at Ham, Picardy, and being of a somewhat adventurous spirit, he crossed the English Channel and became both a British citizen and the secretary of a Scottish nobleman.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] In that capacity, he traveled with his employer on the Continent, particularly spending time in Italy.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] At about 31, he settled in Ghent and was employed by the city, where Adolphe was born, the fifth of nine children, several of whom died in childhood.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Francois died when Adolphe was only seven years old.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Adolphe studied at the Ghent Lycée, where he afterwards started teaching mathematics in 1815 at the age of 19.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] In 1819, he moved to the Athenaeum in Brussels and in the same year he completed his dissertation (*De quibusdam locis geometricis, necnon de curva focal – Of some new properties of the focal distance and some other curves*).
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet received a doctorate in mathematics in 1819 from the University of Ghent.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Shortly thereafter, the young man set out to convince government officials and private donors to build an astronomical observatory in Brussels; he succeeded in 1828.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] He became a member of the Royal Academy in 1820.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] He lectured at the museum for sciences and letters and at the Belgian Military School.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] In 1825, he became a correspondent of the Royal Institute of the Netherlands, in 1827 he became a member.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] In 1839, he was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] From 1841 to 1851, he was a supernumerary associate in the institute, and when it became Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences he became foreign member.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] In 1850, he was elected a foreign member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] In 1825, he married Cécile-Virginie Curtet.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet also founded several statistical journals and societies, and was especially interested in creating international cooperation among statisticians.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] He encouraged the creation of a statistical section of the British Association for the Advancement of Science (BA), which later became the Royal Statistical Society, of which he became the first overseas member.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] In 1853 he chaired both the International Maritime Conference and the first International Statistical Congress.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] He was a founding member of the first *Société des douze*.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] In 1855, Quetelet developed apoplexy, which diminished but did not end his scientific activity.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] He died in Brussels on 17 February 1874, and is buried in the Brussels Cemetery.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] His scientific research encompassed a wide range of different scientific disciplines: meteorology, astronomy, mathematics, statistics, demography, sociology, criminology and history of science.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] He made significant contributions to scientific development, but he also wrote several monographs directed to the general public.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] He founded the Royal Observatory of Belgium, founded or co-founded several national and international statistical societies and scientific journals, and presided over the first series of the International Statistical Congresses.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet was a liberal and an anticlerical, but not an atheist or materialist nor a socialist.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Adolphe Quetelet discovered the optical phenomenon Quetelet rings.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] The new science of probability and statistics was mainly used in astronomy at the time, where it was essential to account for measurement errors around means.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] This was done using the method of least squares.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet was among the first to apply statistics to social science, planning what he called "social physics".
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] He was keenly aware of the overwhelming complexity of social phenomena, and the many variables that needed measurement.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] His goal was to understand the statistical laws underlying such phenomena as crime rates, marriage rates or suicide rates.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] He wanted to explain the values of these variables by other social factors.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] These ideas were rather controversial among other scientists at the time who held that it contradicted the concept of freedom of choice.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] His most influential book was *Sur l'homme et le développement de ses facultés, ou Essai de physique sociale*, published in 1835 (In English translation, it is titled *Treatise on Man*, but a literal translation would be "On Man and the Development of his Faculties, or Essay on Social Physics").
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] In it, he outlines the project of a social physics and describes his concept of the "average man" (*l'homme moyen*) who is characterized by the mean values of measured variables that follow a normal distribution.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] He collected data about many such variables.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet wrote about these values as "ideals" with deviations from them as being less than or more than ideal.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] He saw the average body as an ideal beauty and something to be desired and his work was influential on Francis Galton who coined the term *eugenics*.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet's student Pierre François Verhulst developed the logistic function in the 1830s as a model of population growth; see Logistic function § History for details.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Adolphe Quetelet also had a significant influence on Florence Nightingale who shared with him a religious view of statistics which saw understanding statistics as revealing the work of God in addition to statistics being a force of good administration.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Nightingale met Quetelet in person at the 1860 International Statistical Congress in London, and they corresponded for years afterwards.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet was an influential figure in criminology.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Along with Andre-Michel Guerry, he helped to establish the cartographic school and positivist schools of criminology which made extensive use of statistical techniques.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Through statistical analysis, Quetelet gained insight into the relationships between crime and other social factors.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Among his findings were strong relationships between age and crime, as well as gender and crime.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Other influential factors he found included climate, poverty, education, and alcohol consumption, with his research findings published in *Of the Development of the Propensity to Crime*.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] In his 1835 text on social physics, he presented his theory of human variance around the average, showing human traits were distributed according to a normal curve.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] The existence of such variation provided the basis for later writers, including Darwin, to argue that natural populations contained sufficient variability for artificial or natural selection to operate.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] In terms of influence over later public health agendas, one of Quetelet's lasting legacies was the establishment of a simple measure for classifying people's weight relative to an ideal for their height.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] His proposal, the body mass index (or Quetelet index), has endured with minor variations to the present day.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Anthropometric data is used in modern applications and referenced in the development of every consumer-based product.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Society (ForMemRS) in 1839.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] The asteroid 1239 Queteleta is named after him.
[src:david-starr-jordan/adolphe-quetelet] The title of Quetelet professor at Columbia University is awarded in his name.
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] In it, Lockhart-Mummery imagines Britain as it might be in the 25th century using the device of a series of letters home from a New Zealander.
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] He imagines a world where all male children are sterilised shortly after birth, except for those carefully selected.
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] Those exempt from compulsory sterilisation would provide the "seed" for future generations by artificial insemination.
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] The book has 287 pages and begins with a preface followed by a list of 24 chapter titles.
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] The foreword is given by the author's friend Lord Horder, president of the Eugenics Society, who thought Lockhart-Mummery's theories radical.
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] In the book, Lockhart-Mummery imagines Britain as it might be in the 25th century using the device of a series of letters home from a New Zealander.
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] His central concern is over-population resulting from man's conquest of the natural world and the risk to man's future from disease or famine.
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] He argues that either new sources of food will have to be developed or population will have to be controlled, and for that reason welcomes the increasing use of contraception.
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] Lockhart-Mummery envisages government control of reproduction and imagines a world where "all men, except those approximating the ideal citizen" would be sterilised, and women would breed from the remaining stock, in order to produce "perfection".
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] In the fourth chapter titled "preferential breeding", he proposes that all male children should be sterilised shortly after birth, except for those carefully selected to exclude "bad hereditary factors".
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] Those exempt from compulsory sterilisation he writes, "will become the fathers of the next generation".
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] If pregnancy does not occur she will be allowed to try again.
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] He thought the separation of sexual love from reproduction would have profound social implications for society and possibly give women greater independence.
[src:david-starr-jordan/after-us-or-the-world-as-it-might-be] In the book, he attributes the failure to adopt his policies to "sloppy sentiment" and argues that they will not be adopted until an "autocratic government" arises with the will to act in the interests of all men.
[src:david-starr-jordan/agonomalus-jordani] It is a marine, temperate water-dwelling fish which is known from the northwestern Pacific Ocean, including Japan, the Sea of Japan, and Sakhalin.
[src:david-starr-jordan/agonomalus-jordani] It dwells at a depth range of 10 to 105 metres (33 to 344 ft).
[src:david-starr-jordan/agonomalus-jordani] Males can reach a maximum total length of 18 centimetres (7.1 in), but more commonly reach a TL of 11 centimetres (4.3 in).
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] "***Aktion T4***" (German, pronounced [akˈtsi̯oːn teː fiːɐ]) is the name given to campaigns of mass murder by involuntary euthanasia which targeted people with disabilities and the mentally ill in Nazi Germany.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The term was first used in post-war trials against doctors who had been involved in the killings.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The name T4 is an abbreviation of *Tiergartenstraße* 4, a street address of the Chancellery department set up in early 1940, in the Berlin borough of Tiergarten, which recruited and paid personnel associated with Aktion T4.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Certain German physicians were authorised to select patients "deemed incurably sick, after most critical medical examination" and then administer to them a "mercy death" (*Gnadentod*).
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In October 1939, Adolf Hitler signed a "euthanasia note", backdated to 1 September 1939, which authorised his physician Karl Brandt and *Reichsleiter* Philipp Bouhler to begin the killing.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The killings took place from September 1939 until the end of World War II in Europe in 1945.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Between 275,000 and 300,000 people were killed in psychiatric hospitals in Germany, Austria, occupied Poland, and the Protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia (now the Czech Republic).
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The number of victims was originally recorded as 70,273 but this number has been increased by the discovery of victims listed in the archives of the former East Germany.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] About half of those killed were taken from church-run asylums.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In June 1940, Paul Braune and Fritz von Bodelschwingh, who served as directors of sanatoriums, protested against the killings, being members of the Lutheran Confessing Church.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The Holy See announced on 2 December 1940 that the policy was contrary to divine law and that "the direct killing of an innocent person because of mental or physical defects is not allowed".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Several reasons have been suggested for the killings, including eugenics, racial hygiene, and saving money.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Physicians in German and Austrian asylums continued many of the practices of *Aktion T4* until the defeat of Germany in 1945, in spite of its official cessation in August 1941.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The informal continuation of the policy led to 93,521 "beds emptied" by the end of 1941.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Technology developed under *Aktion T4*, particularly the use of lethal gas on large numbers of people, was taken over by the medical division of the Reich Interior Ministry, along with the personnel of *Aktion T4*, who participated in the mass murder of Jewish people under Operation Reinhard.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The number of people killed was about 200,000 in Germany and Austria, with about 100,000 victims in other European countries.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Following the war, a number of the perpetrators were tried and convicted for murder and crimes against humanity.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] At the beginning of the twentieth century, the sterilisation of people carrying what were considered to be hereditary defects and in some cases those exhibiting what was thought to be hereditary "antisocial" behaviour, was a respectable field of medicine.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Canada, Denmark, Switzerland and the United States had passed laws enabling coerced sterilisation.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Studies conducted in the 1920s ranked Germany as a country that was unusually reluctant to introduce sterilisation legislation.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In his book *Mein Kampf* (1924), Hitler wrote that one day racial hygiene "will appear as a deed greater than the most victorious wars of our present bourgeois era".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In July 1933, the "Law for the Prevention of Hereditarily Diseased Offspring" prescribed compulsory sterilisation for people with conditions thought to be hereditary, such as schizophrenia, epilepsy, Huntington's chorea and "imbecility".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Sterilisation was also legalised for chronic alcoholism and other forms of social deviance.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The law was administered by the Interior Ministry under Wilhelm Frick through special Hereditary Health Courts (*Erbgesundheitsgerichte*), which examined the inmates of nursing homes, asylums, prisons, aged-care homes and special schools, to select those to be sterilised.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] It is estimated that 360,000 people were sterilised under this law between 1933 and 1939.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The policy and research agenda of racial hygiene and eugenics were promoted by Emil Kraepelin.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Within the Nazi administration, the idea of including in the programme people with physical disabilities had to be expressed carefully, because the Reich Minister of Propaganda, Joseph Goebbels, had a deformed right leg.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] After 1937, the acute shortage of labour in Germany arising from rearmament, meant that anyone capable of work was deemed to be "useful", exempted from the law and the rate of sterilisation declined.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The term *Aktion T4* is a post-war coining; contemporary German terms included *Euthanasie* (euthanasia) and *Gnadentod* (merciful death).
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The T4 programme stemmed from the Nazi Party policy of "racial hygiene", a belief that the German people needed to be cleansed of "racial enemies," including the mentally ill and disabled.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] New insulin shock treatments were used by German psychiatrists to find out if patients with schizophrenia were curable.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Karl Brandt, Hitler's doctor, and Hans Lammers, the head of the Reich Chancellery, testified after the war that Hitler had told them as early as 1933—when the sterilisation law was passed—that he favoured the killing of the incurably ill but recognised that public opinion would not accept this.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In 1935, Hitler told the Leader of Reich Doctors, Gerhard Wagner, that the question could not be taken up in peacetime; "Such a problem could be more smoothly and easily carried out in war." He wrote that he intended to "radically solve" the problem of the mental asylums in such an event.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] On 18 August 1939, three weeks after the killing of Kretschmar, the *Reich Committee for the Scientific Registering of Hereditary and Congenital Illnesses* was established to register sick children or newborns identified as defective.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The secret killing of infants began in 1939 and increased after the war started.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] By 1941, more than 5,000 children had been killed.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Hitler was in favour of killing those whom he judged to be *lebensunwertes Leben* ('Life unworthy of life').
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] This issue, according to the Nazi regime, assumed a new urgency in wartime.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Pfannmüller advocated killing by a gradual decrease of food, which he believed was more merciful than poison injections.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The German eugenics movement had an extreme wing even before the Nazis came to power.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] As early as 1920, Alfred Hoche and Karl Binding advocated killing people whose lives were "unworthy of life" (*lebensunwertes Leben*).
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Darwinism was interpreted by them as justification of the demand for "beneficial" genes and eradication of the "harmful" ones.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Robert Lifton wrote, "The argument went that the best young men died in war, causing a loss to the *Volk* of the best genes.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The genes of those who did not fight (the worst genes) then proliferated freely, accelerating biological and cultural degeneration".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The advocacy of eugenics in Germany gained ground after 1930, when the Depression was used to excuse cuts in funding to state mental hospitals, creating squalor and overcrowding.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Many German eugenicists were nationalists and antisemites, who embraced the Nazi regime with enthusiasm.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Many were appointed to positions in the Health Ministry and German research institutes.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Their ideas were gradually adopted by the majority of the German medical profession, from which Jewish and communist doctors were soon purged.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In the 1930s, the Nazi Party had carried out a campaign of propaganda in favour of euthanasia.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The National Socialist Racial and Political Office (NSRPA) produced leaflets, posters and short films to be shown in cinemas, pointing out to Germans the cost of maintaining asylums for the incurably ill and insane.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Brandt and Bouhler were authorised to approve applications to kill children in relevant circumstances, though Bouhler left the details to subordinates such as Brack and SA-*Oberführer* Werner Blankenburg.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Extermination centres were established at six existing psychiatric hospitals: Bernburg, Brandenburg, Grafeneck, Hadamar, Hartheim, and Sonnenstein.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] One thousand children under the age of 17 were killed at the institutions Am Spiegelgrund and Gugging in Austria.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] They played a crucial role in developments leading to the Holocaust.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] As a related aspect of the "medical" and scientific basis of this programme, the Nazi doctors took thousands of brains from 'euthanasia' victims for research.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] From August 1939, the Interior Ministry registered children with disabilities, requiring doctors and midwives to report all cases of newborns with severe disabilities; the 'guardian' consent element soon disappeared.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The reports were assessed by a panel of medical experts, of whom three were required to give their approval before a child could be killed.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The Ministry used deceit when dealing with parents or guardians, particularly in Catholic areas, where parents were generally uncooperative.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Parents were told that their children were being sent to "Special Sections", where they would receive improved treatment.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The children sent to these centres were kept for "assessment" for a few weeks and then killed by injection of toxic chemicals, typically phenol; their deaths were recorded as "pneumonia".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Autopsies were usually performed and brain samples were taken to be used for "medical research".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Post mortem examinations apparently helped to ease the consciences of many of those involved, giving them the feeling that there was a genuine medical purpose to the killings.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The most notorious of these institutions in Austria was Am Spiegelgrund, where from 1940 to 1945, 789 children were killed by lethal injection, gas poisoning and physical abuse.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Children's brains were preserved in jars of formaldehyde and stored in the basement of the clinic and in the private collection of Heinrich Gross, one of the institution's directors, until 2001.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] When the Second World War began in September 1939, less rigorous standards of assessment and a quicker approval process were adopted.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] More pressure was placed on parents to agree to their children being sent away.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Many parents suspected what was happening and refused consent, especially when it became apparent that institutions for children with disabilities were being systematically cleared of their charges.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The parents were warned that they could lose custody of all their children and if that did not suffice, the parents could be threatened with call-up for 'labour duty'.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The last child to be killed under *Aktion T4* was Richard Jenne on 29 May 1945, in the children's ward of the Kaufbeuren-Irsee state hospital in Bavaria, Germany, more than three weeks after US Army troops had occupied the town.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Brandt and Bouhler developed plans to expand the programme of euthanasia to adults.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In July 1939 they held a meeting attended by Conti and Professor Werner Heyde, head of the SS medical department.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] This meeting agreed to arrange a national register of all institutionalised people with mental illnesses or physical disabilities.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The first adults with disabilities to be killed en masse by the Nazi regime were Poles.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] After the invasion on 1 September 1939, adults with disabilities were shot by the SS men of *Einsatzkommando* 16, *Selbstschutz* and *EK-Einmann* under the command of SS-*Sturmbannführer* Rudolf Tröger, overseen by Reinhard Heydrich, during Operation Tannenberg.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] All hospitals and mental asylums of the Wartheland were emptied.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The region was incorporated into Germany and earmarked for resettlement by *Volksdeutsche* following the German conquest of Poland.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In the Danzig (now Gdańsk) area, some 7,000 Polish patients of institutions were shot.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Similar measures were taken in other areas of Poland destined for incorporation into Germany.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In December 1939, *Reichsführer-SS* Heinrich Himmler witnessed one of these gassings, ensuring that this invention would later be put to much wider uses.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The idea of killing adult mental patients soon spread from occupied Poland to adjoining areas of Germany, probably because Nazi Party and SS officers in these areas were most familiar with what was happening in Poland.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] These were the areas where Germans wounded from the Polish campaign were expected to be accommodated, which created a demand for hospital space.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The *Gauleiter* of Pomerania, Franz Schwede-Coburg, sent 1,400 patients from five Pomeranian hospitals to undisclosed locations in occupied Poland, where they were shot.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The *Gauleiter* of East Prussia, Erich Koch, had 1,600 patients killed out of sight.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] More than 8,000 Germans were killed in this initial wave of killings carried out on the orders of local officials, although Himmler certainly knew and approved of them.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The legal basis for the programme was a 1939 letter from Hitler, not a formal "Führer's decree" with the force of law.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Hitler bypassed Conti, the Health Minister and his department, who might have raised questions about the legality of the programme and entrusted it to Bouhler and Brandt.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The killings were administered by Viktor Brack and his staff from *Tiergartenstraße* 4, disguised as the "Charitable Foundation for Cure and Institutional Care" offices which served as the front and was supervised by Bouhler and Brandt.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The officials in charge included Herbert Linden, who had been involved in the child killing programme; Ernst-Robert Grawitz, chief physician of the SS and August Becker, an SS chemist.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The officials selected the doctors who were to carry out the operational part of the programme; based on political reliability as long-term Nazis, professional reputation and sympathy for radical eugenics.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The list included physicians who had proved their worth in the child-killing programme, such as Unger, Heinze and Hermann Pfannmüller.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The recruits were mostly psychiatrists, notably Professor Carl Schneider of Heidelberg, Professor Max de Crinis of Berlin and Professor Paul Nitsche from the Sonnenstein state institution.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Heyde became the operational leader of the programme, succeeded later by Nitsche.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The conditions included schizophrenia, epilepsy, Huntington's chorea, advanced syphilis, senile dementia, paralysis, encephalitis and "terminal neurological conditions generally".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Many doctors and administrators assumed that the reports were to identify inmates who were capable of being drafted for "labour service" and tended to overstate the degree of incapacity of their patients, to protect them from labour conscription.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] When some institutions refused to co-operate, teams of T4 doctors, or Nazi medical students, visited and compiled the lists, sometimes in a haphazard and ideologically motivated way.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In 1940, all Jewish patients were removed from institutions and killed.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] As with child inmates, adults were assessed by a panel of experts, working at the *Tiergartenstraße* offices.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The experts were required to make their judgements on the reports, not medical histories or examinations.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Sometimes they dealt with hundreds of reports at a time.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] On each they marked a **+** (death), a **-** (life), or occasionally a **?** meaning that they were unable to decide.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Three "death" verdicts condemned the person and as with reviews of children, the process became less rigorous, the range of conditions considered "unsustainable" grew broader and zealous Nazis further down the chain of command increasingly made decisions on their own initiative.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The first gassings in Germany proper took place in January 1940 at the Brandenburg Euthanasia Centre.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The operation was headed by Brack, who said "the needle belongs in the hand of the doctor".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Bottled pure carbon monoxide gas was used.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] At trials, Brandt described the process as a "major advance in medical history".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In addition to Brandenburg, the killing centres included Grafeneck Castle in Baden-Württemberg (10,824 dead), Schloss Hartheim near Linz in Austria (over 18,000 dead), Sonnenstein in Saxony (15,000 dead), Bernburg in Saxony-Anhalt and Hadamar in Hesse (14,494 dead).
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The same facilities were also used to kill mentally sound prisoners transferred from concentration camps in Germany, Austria and occupied parts of Poland.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Condemned patients were transferred from their institutions to new centres in T4 Charitable Ambulance buses, called the Community Patients Transports Service.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] They were run by teams of SS men wearing white coats, to give it an air of medical care.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] To prevent the families and doctors of the patients from tracing them, the patients were often first sent to transit centres in major hospitals, where they were supposedly assessed.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] They were moved again to *special treatment* (*Sonderbehandlung*) centres.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Families were sent letters explaining that owing to wartime regulations, it was not possible for them to visit relatives in these centres.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Most of these patients were killed within 24 hours of arriving at the centres and their bodies cremated.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Some bodies were dissected for medical research whilst others had their gold teeth extracted.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] For every person killed, a death certificate was prepared, giving a false but plausible cause of death.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] This was sent to the family along with an urn of ashes (random ashes, since the victims were cremated *en masse*).
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The preparation of thousands of falsified death certificates took up most of the working day of the doctors who operated the centres.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] During 1940, the centres at Brandenburg, Grafeneck and Hartheim killed nearly 10,000 people each, while another 6,000 were killed at Sonnenstein.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In all, about 35,000 people were killed in T4 operations that year.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Operations at Brandenburg and Grafeneck were wound up at the end of the year, partly because the areas they served had been cleared and partly because of public opposition.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In 1941, however, the centres at Bernburg and Sonnenstein increased their operations, while Hartheim (where Wirth and Franz Stangl were successively commandants) continued as before.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Another 35,000 people were killed before August 1941, when the T4 programme was officially shut down by Hitler.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Even after that date the centres continued to be used to kill concentration camp inmates: eventually some 20,000 people in this category were killed.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In 1971, Gitta Sereny conducted interviews with Stangl, who was in prison in Düsseldorf, having been convicted of co-responsibility for killing 900,000 people, while commandant of the Sobibor and Treblinka extermination camps in Poland.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Stangl gave Sereny a detailed account of the operations of the T4 programme based on his time as commandant of the killing facility at the Hartheim institute.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] He described how the inmates of asylums were removed and transported by bus to Hartheim.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Some were in no mental state to know what was happening to them but many were perfectly sane and for them forms of deception were used.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] They were told they were at a special clinic where they would receive improved treatment and were given a brief medical examination on arrival.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] They were induced to enter what appeared to be a shower block, where they were gassed with carbon monoxide.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The ruse was also used at extermination camps.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Some of the victims knew their fate and tried to defend themselves.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The SS functionaries and hospital staff associated with *Aktion T4* in the German Reich were paid from the central office at *Tiergartenstraße* 4 in Berlin from the spring of 1940.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The SS and police from *SS-Sonderkommando Lange* responsible for murdering the majority of patients in the annexed territories of Poland since October 1939, took their salaries from the normal police fund, supervised by the administration of the newly formed *Wartheland* district.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The programme in Germany and occupied Poland was overseen by Heinrich Himmler.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In the German T4 centres there was at least the semblance of legality in keeping records and writing letters.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In Polish psychiatric hospitals no one was left behind.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Killings were inflicted using gas-vans, sealed army bunkers and machine guns; families were not informed about the murdered relatives and the empty wards were handed over to the SS.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] After the official end of the euthanasia programme in 1941, most of the personnel and high-ranking officials, as well as gassing technology and the techniques used to deceive victims, were transferred under the jurisdiction of the national medical division of the Reich Interior Ministry.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Further gassing experiments with the use of mobile gas chambers (*Einsatzwagen*) were conducted at Soldau concentration camp by Herbert Lange following Operation Barbarossa.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Lange was appointed commander of the Chełmno extermination camp in December 1941.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] He was given three gas vans by the Reich Security Main Office (RSHA), converted by the Gaubschat GmbH in Berlin and before February 1942, killed 3,830 Polish Jews and around 4,000 Romani, under the guise of "resettlement".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] After the Wannsee conference, implementation of gassing technology was accelerated by Heydrich.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Beginning in the spring of 1942, three killing factories were built secretly in east-central Poland.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The *SS* officers responsible for the earlier *Aktion T4*, including Wirth, Stangl and Irmfried Eberl, had important roles in the implementation of the "Final Solution" for the next two years.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The first killing centre, equipped with stationary gas chambers, modelled on technology developed under *Aktion T4*, was established at Bełżec in the General Government territory of occupied Poland; the decision preceded the Wannsee Conference of January 1942 by three months.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In January 1939, Brack commissioned a paper from Professor of Moral Theology at the University of Paderborn, Joseph Mayer, on the likely reactions of the churches in the event of a state euthanasia programme being instituted.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Mayer – a longstanding euthanasia advocate – reported that the churches would not oppose such a programme if it was seen to be in the national interest.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Brack showed this paper to Hitler in July and it may have increased his confidence that the "euthanasia" programme would be acceptable to German public opinion.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Notably, when Sereny interviewed Mayer shortly before his death in 1967, he denied that he formally condoned the killing of people with disabilities but no copies of this paper are known to survive.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Some bureaucrats opposed the T4 programme; Lothar Kreyssig, a district judge and member of the Confessing Church, wrote to Justice Minister Franz Gürtner protesting that the action was illegal since no law or formal decree from Hitler had authorised it.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Gürtner replied, "If you cannot recognise the will of the Führer as a source of law, then you cannot remain a judge" and had Kreyssig dismissed.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Hitler had a policy of not issuing written instructions for matters which could later be condemned by the international community, but made an exception when he provided Bouhler and Brack with written authority for the T4 programme.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Hitler wrote a confidential letter in October 1939 to overcome opposition within the German state bureaucracy.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Hitler told Bouhler that, "the Führer's Chancellery must under no circumstances be seen to be active in this matter".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Gürtner had to be shown Hitler's letter in August 1940 to gain his co-operation.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In the towns where the killing centres were located, some people saw the inmates arrive in buses, saw smoke from the crematoria chimneys and noticed that the buses were returning empty.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In Hadamar, ashes containing human hair rained down on the town and despite the strictest orders, some of the staff at the killing centres talked about what was going on.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In some cases families could tell that the causes of death in certificates were false, e.g. when a patient was claimed to have died of appendicitis, even though his appendix had been removed some years earlier.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In other cases, families in the same town would receive death certificates on the same day.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In May 1941, the Frankfurt County Court wrote to Gürtner describing scenes in Hadamar, where children shouted in the streets that people were being taken away in buses to be gassed.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] During 1940, rumours of what was taking place spread and many Germans withdrew their relatives from asylums and sanatoria to care for them at home, often with great expense and difficulty.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In some places doctors and psychiatrists co-operated with families to have patients discharged or if the families could afford it, transferred them to private clinics beyond the reach of T4.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Other doctors "re-diagnosed" patients so that they no longer met the T4 criteria, which risked exposure when Nazi zealots from Berlin conducted inspections.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In Kiel, Professor Hans Gerhard Creutzfeldt managed to save nearly all of his patients.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Lifton listed a handful of psychiatrists and administrators who opposed the killings; many doctors collaborated, either through ignorance, agreement with Nazi eugenicist policies or fear of the regime.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Protest letters were sent to the Reich Chancellery and the Ministry of Justice, some from Nazi Party members.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The first open protest against the removal of people from asylums took place at Absberg in Franconia in February 1941 and others followed.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The SD report on the incident at Absberg noted that "the removal of residents from the Ottilien Home has caused a great deal of unpleasantness" and described large crowds of Catholic townspeople, among them Party members, protesting against the action.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Similar petitions and protests occurred throughout Austria as rumours spread of mass killings at the Hartheim Euthanasia Centre and of mysterious deaths at the children's clinic, *Am Spiegelgrund* in Vienna.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Anna Wödl, a nurse and mother of a child with a disability, vehemently petitioned to Hermann Linden at the Reich Ministry of the Interior in Berlin to prevent her son, Alfred, from being transferred from Gugging, where he lived and which also became a euthanasia center.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Wödl failed and Alfred was sent to *Am Spiegelgrund*, where he was killed on 22 February 1941.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] His brain was preserved in formaldehyde for "research" and stored in the clinic for sixty years.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The Lutheran theologian Friedrich von Bodelschwingh (director of the Bethel Institution for Epilepsy at Bielefeld) and Pastor Paul-Gerhard Braune (director of the Hoffnungstal Institution near Berlin) protested.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Bodelschwingh negotiated directly with Brandt and indirectly with Hermann Göring, whose cousin was a prominent psychiatrist.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Braune had meetings with Gürtner, who was always dubious about the legality of the programme.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Gürtner later wrote a strongly worded letter to Hitler protesting against it; Hitler did not read it but was told about it by Lammers.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] On 4 December 1940, Reinhold Sautter, the Supreme Church Councillor of the Württemberg State Church, complained to the Nazi Ministerial Councillor Eugen Stähle against the murders in Grafeneck Castle.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Stähle said "The fifth commandment Thou shalt not kill, is no commandment of God but a Jewish invention".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Bishop Heinrich Wienken of Berlin, a leading member of the Caritas Association, was selected by the Fulda episcopal synod to represent the views of the Catholic Church in meetings with T4 operatives.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Galen's sermons were not reported in the German press but were circulated illegally in leaflets.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The text was dropped by the Royal Air Force over German troops.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Evans wrote that "This was the strongest, most explicit and most widespread protest movement against any policy since the beginning of the Third Reich".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Local Nazis asked for Galen to be arrested but Goebbels told Hitler that such action would provoke a revolt in Westphalia and Hitler decided to wait until after the war to take revenge.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] In 1986, Lifton wrote, "Nazi leaders faced the prospect of either having to imprison prominent, highly admired clergymen and other protesters – a course with consequences in terms of adverse public reaction they greatly feared – or else end the programme".
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Evans considered it "at least possible, even indeed probable" that the T4 programme would have continued beyond Hitler's initial quota of 70,000 deaths but for the public reaction to Galen's sermon.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Burleigh called assumptions that the sermon affected Hitler's decision to suspend the T4 programme "wishful thinking" and noted that the various Church hierarchies did not complain after the transfer of T4 personnel to *Aktion Reinhard*.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Galen had detailed knowledge of the euthanasia programme by July 1940 but did not speak out until almost a year after Protestants had begun to protest.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] On 29 June 1943, Pope Pius XII issued the encyclical *Mystici corporis Christi*, in which he condemned the fact that "physically deformed people, mentally disturbed people and hereditarily ill people have at times been robbed of their lives" in Germany.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] On 24 August 1941, Hitler ordered the suspension of the T4 killings.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] After the invasion of the Soviet Union in June, many T4 personnel were transferred to the eastern front.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The projected death total for the T4 programme of 70,000 deaths had been reached by August 1941.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The termination of the T4 programme did not end the killing of people with disabilities; from the end of 1941, on the initiative of institute directors and local party leaders, the killing of adults and children continued, albeit less systematically, until the end of the war.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] After the bombing of Hamburg in July 1943, occupants of old age homes were killed.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] Hilda Wernicke, Berlin, August 1946, testimony was given that "500 old, broken women" who had survived the bombing of Stettin in June 1944 were euthanised at the Meseritz-Oberwalde Asylum.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The Hartheim, Bernberg, Sonnenstein and Hadamar centres continued in use as "wild euthanasia" centres to kill people sent from all over Germany, until 1945.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] The methods were lethal injection or starvation, those employed before use of gas chambers.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] By the end of 1941, about 100,000 people had been killed in the T4 programme.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p01] From mid-1941, concentration camp prisoners too feeble or too much trouble to keep alive were murdered after a cursory psychiatric examination under Action 14f13.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p02] After the war trials were held in connection with the Nazi euthanasia programme at various places including Dresden, Frankfurt, Graz, Nuremberg and Tübingen.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p02] In December 1946 an American military tribunal (commonly called the Doctors' trial) prosecuted 23 doctors and administrators for their roles in war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p02] These crimes included the systematic killing of those deemed "unworthy of life", including people with mental disabilities, the people who were institutionalised mentally ill and people with physical impairments.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p02] After 140 days of proceedings, including the testimony of 85 witnesses and the submission of 1,500 documents, in August 1947 the court pronounced 16 of the defendants guilty.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p02] Seven were sentenced to death; the men, including Brandt and Brack, were executed on 2 June 1948.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p02] Earlier, in 1945, American forces tried seven staff members of the Hadamar killing centre for the killing of Soviet and Polish nationals, which was within their jurisdiction under international law, as these were the citizens of wartime allies.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p02] (Hadamar was within the American Zone of Occupation in Germany.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p02] This was before the Allied resolution of December 1945, to prosecute individuals for "crimes against humanity" for such mass atrocities.) Alfons Klein, Heinrich Ruoff and Karl Willig were sentenced to death and executed; the other four were given long prison sentences.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p02] In 1946, reconstructed German courts tried members of the Hadamar staff for the murders of nearly 15,000 German citizens.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p02] The chief physician, Adolf Wahlmann and Irmgard Huber, the head nurse, were convicted.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p02] The Stasi (Ministry for State Security) of East Germany stored around 30,000 files of *Aktion T4* in their archives.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p02] Those files became available to the public after German Reunification in 1990, leading to a new wave of research on these wartime crimes.
[src:david-starr-jordan/aktion-t4-p02] The German national memorial to the people with disabilities murdered by the Nazis was dedicated in 2014 in Berlin.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:david-starr-jordan/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:david-starr-jordan/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan was also a strong supporter of eugenics, and his published views expressed a fear of "race-degeneration", asserting that cattle and human beings are "governed by the same laws of selection".
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] He was an antimilitarist since he believed that war killed off the best members of the gene pool, and he initially opposed American involvement in World War I.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan was born in Gainesville, New York, and grew up on a farm in upstate New York.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] His parents made an unorthodox decision to educate him at a local girls' high school.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] His middle name, Starr, does not appear in early census records, and was apparently self-selected; he had begun using it by the time that he was enrolled at Cornell.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] He said that it was in honour of his mother's devotion to the minister Thomas Starr King but also due to his admiration for the night sky which he expressed at a young age.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] He was inspired by Louis Agassiz to pursue his studies in ichthyology.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In the mid-19th century Agassiz was incomparably influential and trained "nearly all" of the leading naturalists in the United States.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Simultaneously, according to historian Donald Yacovone, "His revulsion for African Americans and his insistence on their inherent inferiority knew no limits.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] The influence of [Agassiz's] damaging ideas cannot be overestimated." Jordan was part of the first freshman class of undergraduates at Cornell University, where he graduated in 1872 with a master's degree in botany.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In his autobiography, *The Days of a Man*, he wrote, "During the three years which followed [my entrance as a 'belated' freshman in March 1869], I completed all the requirements for a degree of Bachelor of Science, besides about two year of advanced work in Botany.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Taking this last into consideration, the faculty conferred on me at graduation in June 1872, the advanced degree of Master of Science instead of the conventional Bachelor's Degree ... it was afterward voted not to grant any second degree within a year after the Bachelor had been received.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] I was placed, quite innocently, in the position of being the only graduate of Cornell to merge two degrees into one." His master's thesis was on the topic "The Wild Flowers of Wyoming County".
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan initially taught natural history courses at several small Midwestern colleges and secondary schools, including at Indianapolis High School.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In 1875, while in Indianapolis, Jordan obtained a Doctor of Medicine degree from Indiana Medical College.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] The Indiana Medical College in Indianapolis opened in 1869, but merged out of existence in 1878.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Standards at the college were not particularly high.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan also holds an honorary PhD, awarded to him by Butler University in 1877.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In 1879, Jordan was accepted into the natural history faculty of Indiana University Bloomington, where he served as a professor of zoology.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In January 1885, Jordan began his tenure as president of Indiana University and became the nation's youngest university president at only 34 and the first Indiana University president who was not an ordained minister.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] He improved the university's finances and public image, doubled its enrollment, and instituted an elective system; like Cornell's, it was an early application of the modern liberal arts curriculum.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In March 1891, he was approached by Leland and Jane Stanford, who offered him the presidency of Leland Stanford Junior University, which was about to open in California.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Andrew Dickson White, the co-founder and first president of Cornell University, who offered him the position, recommended Jordan to the Stanfords based on an educational philosophy fit with the Stanfords' vision of a nonsectarian co-educational school with a liberal arts curriculum.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan quickly accepted the offer, arrived at Stanford in June 1891, and immediately set about recruiting faculty for the university's planned September opening.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Pressed for time, he drew heavily on his own acquaintances; most of the 15 founding professors came either from Cornell or Indiana University.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] That first year at Stanford, Jordan was instrumental in establishing the university's Hopkins Marine Station.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] He served Stanford as president until 1913 and then chancellor until his retirement in 1916.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] The university decided not to renew his three-year-term as chancellor in 1916.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] As the years went on, Jordan became increasingly alienated from the university.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] While he was chancellor, he was elected president of the National Education Association.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan was a member in the Bohemian Club and the University Club in San Francisco.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan served as a director of the Sierra Club from 1892 to 1903.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1905.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In 1905, he was one of the first professors to build a summer home at the northeast corner of Camino Real and 7th Avenue, on what became known as "Professors' Row" in Carmel-by-the-Sea, California.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] He was good friends with Stanford University professor of entomology Vernon Lyman Kellogg, who also lived in Carmel.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In 1899, Jordan delivered an essay at Stanford on behalf of racial segregation and racial purity.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In the essay, Jordan argued that "...a race of men or a herd of cattle are governed by the same laws of selection." Jordan expressed concern about "race degeneration" that would occur unless efforts were made to maintain "racial unity".
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan argued that peace was preferable to warfare because war removed the strongest men from the gene pool.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan was president of the World Peace Foundation from 1910 to 1914 and president of the World Peace Conference in 1915 and initially opposed American entry into World War I although he changed his position in 1917 after he became convinced that a German victory would threaten democracy.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] An expanded version of the essay was delivered in Philadelphia at the 200th anniversary of Benjamin Franklin's birth in 1906 and printed by the American Philosophical Society.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] The following year, an expanded version of the original essay with an embossed cover was published by Beacon Press in Boston under the new main title "The Human Harvest" and the same subtitle.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In 1915, Jordan published an "extended treatise on the same subject" titled *War and Breed* again through the Beacon Press in Boston.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Here Jordan defines and begins to employ the relatively recent term "eugenics" and its opposite "dysgenics".
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] After Jordan's death, the Human Betterment Foundation, a political eugenics-advocacy organization that advocated for compulsory sterilization legislation in the United States, published a newspaper advertisement claiming Jordan as one of its prominent members.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] The Foundation published *Sterilization for Human Betterment*, advocating for legislation that would compel sterilization of the disabled and violent felons, allow for anyone in the public to voluntarily seek medical sterilization, and legalize the use of contraception.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In 1905, Jordan launched an apparent coverup of the murder of Stanford University co-founder Jane Stanford.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] While vacationing in Oahu, Stanford had suddenly died of strychnine poisoning according to the local coroner's jury.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan then sailed to Hawaii, hired a physician to investigate the case, and declared she had in fact died of heart failure, a condition whose symptoms bear no relationship to those that were actually observed.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan's motive has been a subject of speculation.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] One possibility is that he was acting to protect the reputation of the university, as its finances were precarious, and a scandal might have damaged fundraising.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] He had written the president of Stanford's board of trustees, offered several explanations for Stanford's death, and suggested they select whichever was most suitable.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Since Stanford had a difficult relationship with him and reportedly planned to remove him from his position at the university, he might have had a motive to eliminate suspicions about an unsolved crime.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan's version of Stanford's demise was largely accepted until the appearance of several publications in 2003 arguing that she was murdered.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In retirement, Jordan remained active, writing on ichthyology, world relations, peace, and his autobiography.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Although a proponent of eugenics, Jordan was skeptical of certain other pseudoscientific claims.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] He coined the term "sciosophy" to describe the "systematized ignorance" of the pseudoscientist.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] His later work, *The Higher Foolishness*, inspired the philosopher Martin Gardner to write his treatise on scientific skepticism, *Fads and Fallacies in the Name of Science*.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan married Susan Bowen (1845–1885), a biologist and a graduate of Mount Holyoke College, whom he met at Louis Agassiz's Penikese Island Summer School of Science, in her hometown of Peru, Massachusetts, on March 10, 1875.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] She died at age 39, after 10 years of marriage, following a brief illness.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] At the time of their marriage, two years after his first wife's death, Knight was 21 years old and Jordan was 36.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] They met while he was serving as president of Indiana University.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Two of his daughters, Thora and Barbara, died in childhood.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] His son Eric died in 1926 at age 22 in a traffic accident near Gilroy, California.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Eric had participated in a paleontological expedition to the Revillagigedo Islands and was considering an academic career.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan's papers are housed at Stanford University.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] On September 19, 1931, Jordan died at his home on the Stanford University campus after suffering a series of strokes over two years.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] The David Starr Jordan "Namesake Tree" at the University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa Campus Arboretum, an Indian rubber tree, known as *Ficus elastica*, was given to Jordan at the outset of a trip to Japan, and planted by him on December 11, 1922, now listed as an Exceptional Tree of Hawai‘i.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In 1966, the fisheries research ship *David Starr Jordan* was commissioned for service with the United States Fish and Wildlife Service's Bureau of Commercial Fisheries.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] The ship later served in the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration fleet as NOAAS *David Starr Jordan* (R 444) before it was decommissioned in 2010 and sold to a private company, who renamed it the R/V *Ocean Starr*.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] During the early 20th century several schools were named after him or in his honor.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] However, after 2018, most of them were renamed, as his eugenics activities became well known.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Since Jordan was closely associated with both Indiana University and Stanford University, both schools named buildings and other campus features after him.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] However, as his reputation became more controversial in the 2020s, they acted to remove Jordan's name from their respective campuses.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Stanford honored its former president in 1917 by renaming its zoology building, built in 1899, to Jordan Hall.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Other campus features were named Jordan Quad, Jordan Modulars, and Jordan Way.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In October 2020 the Stanford Board of Trustees voted unanimously, on the recommendation of an advisory committee, to remove Jordan's name from all four facilities.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] The former Jordan Hall was to be referred to as Building 420 until a permanent name could be selected sometime the following year.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Stanford President Marc Tessier-Lavigne was charged to rename Jordan Quad and Jordan Modulars; however, Tessier-Lavigne was not able to accomplish this task before he left Stanford in 2023.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] When Indiana University built a new building for its biology department in 1956, the building was named in honor of Jordan, its former president and biology faculty member.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In October 2020 the Indiana University Board of Trustees voted overwhelmingly to remove Jordan's name from the biology building as well as a parking garage and a "river" (actually a small creek) that runs through the center of the campus.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan's name was stripped from these places immediately after the trustee meeting had concluded, and they were given temporary, generic names to be used until permanent names could be selected the following year.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Jordan Hall, the Jordan River and the Jordan Avenue Parking Garage became respectively the Biology Building, the Campus River, and the East Parking Garage.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In August 2021, staff members of the Biology Department sent a petition to the new IU President Pamela Whitten urging the university leadership to rename the Biology Building in honor of James P.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Holland, an African-American IU alumnus, award-winning former faculty member and endocrinologist who died in 1998.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Indiana President President Michael McRobbie requested the University Naming Committee to work with the city of Bloomington to find a name as a replacement for Jordan Avenue, a thoroughfare that is owned in part by IU and in part by the city.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] As of October 2020, there were calls in the Bloomington City Council for Jordan Avenue to be renamed.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In April 2021, the Mayor of Bloomington created a seven-member task force to investigate possible replacement names for Jordan Avenue.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In September 2021, the City of Bloomington Plan Commission announced that it approved the renaming of Jordan Avenue to Eagleson Avenue while IU is in the process of renaming its section of the street to Fuller Lane pending approval by the IU Renaming Committee and IU's board of trustees.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] The city planned to complete their street renaming by February 2022.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Both new street names honor prominent African-American families who moved to Bloomington after being born into slavery.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] In December 2021, IU's board of trustees reconsidered their decision to rename the university's section of the street as Fuller Lane by adopting Eagleson Avenue as the new name for the university-owned section of Jordan Avenue.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] As late as October 2024, the Indiana University South Bend campus had a scholarship named in honor of Jordan that enables its students to study outside of the United States for a short period.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Starting in 1986, the David Starr Jordan Prize was funded as a joint endowment by Cornell University, Indiana University, and Stanford University.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Every three years it was awarded to a young scientist (under 40 years) who made contributions in one of Jordan's interests of evolution, ecology, population or organismal biology.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] The prize was last awarded in 2015 to Daniel Bolnick, a professor of integrative biology at the University of Texas at Austin.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] As Jordan's reputation became more controversial over his support of eugenics, and particularly after the removal of Jordan's name from buildings on the campuses of Stanford and Indiana universities in 2020, there were calls to rename the prize.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] The prize was officially discontinued in 2020 and the endowment funds were returned to their respective universities.
[src:david-starr-jordan/david-starr-jordan] Numerous genera and species bear the name Jordan.
